04619nam a22006735i 9781477314661DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212017txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017009406  a97814773146617 a10.7560/3142962doi  a(DE-B1597)588425  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aHE310.H8bS53 2017 7aHIS0361302bisacsh1 aShelton, Kyle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPower Moves :bTransportation, Politics, and Development in Houston /cKyle Shelton. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFig. 0.1. Houston Highway and Rail Map with Case Studies Highlighted -- tIntroduction -- t1 Building a Highway Metropolis: The Origins and Advent of Houston’s Postwar Growth -- t2 Whose Highways? Planning, Politics, and Consequences -- t3 “Only You Can Prevent Another Freeway”: The Harrisburg Freeway and the Struggle to Shape a Neighborhood -- t4 Infrastructural Elections: Transit Referenda in the 1970s -- t5 By Road or by Rail? The 1983 Transit Debate -- t6 The Legacies and Limits of Infrastructural Citizenship -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince World War II, Houston has become a burgeoning, internationally connected metropolis—and a sprawling, car-dependent city. In 1950, it possessed only one highway, the Gulf Freeway, which ran between Houston and Galveston. Today, Houston and Harris County have more than 1,200 miles of highways, and a third major loop is under construction nearly thirty miles out from the historic core. Highways have driven every aspect of Houston’s postwar development, from the physical layout of the city to the political process that has transformed both the transportation network and the balance of power between governing elites and ordinary citizens. Power Moves examines debates around the planning, construction, and use of highway and public transportation systems in Houston. Kyle Shelton shows how Houstonians helped shape the city’s growth by attending city council meetings, writing letters to the highway commission, and protesting the destruction of homes to make way for freeways, which happened in both affluent and low-income neighborhoods. He demonstrates that these assertions of what he terms “infrastructural citizenship” opened up the transportation decision-making process to meaningful input from the public and gave many previously marginalized citizens a more powerful voice in civic affairs. Power Moves also reveals the long-lasting results of choosing highway and auto-based infrastructure over other transit options and the resulting challenges that Houstonians currently face as they grapple with how best to move forward from the consequences and opportunities created by past choices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aCity planningzTexaszHoustonxCitizen participation. 0aCity planning-Texas-Houston-Citizen participation. 0aTransportation and statezTexaszHouston. 0aTransportation and state-Texas-Houston. 0aTransportationzTexaszHoustonxHistory. 0aTransportation-Texas-Houston-History. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / Southwest (AZ, NM, OK, TX).2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31429640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477314661423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477314661/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK